snippet.textDisplay: One thing I have to disagree with Lamar Hunt. He may have come up with the idea of adding the Roman numeral to the Super Bowl supposedly to clear up confusion because the year of the Super Bowl takes place differently than the year of the regular season. Well, I thought it was partly overcompensation because the Super Bowl was such a young event and didn't have the same amount of history as the World Series had. But now I'm having trouble remembering which Super Bowl went with which year. With the NBA Finals and the Stanley Cup, we understand that the season takes place the year before the championship. Why not the Super Bowl? Why can't we just call this the 2020 Super Bowl instead of Super Bowl 54?

snippet.textDisplay:
Super Bowl III is arguably one of the most important football games in professional sports history, but there are a number of people who misunderstand the importance. I heard somebody on the radio who said that Joe Namath was inducted into Canton mostly because of Super Bowl III, which is true. However, he THEN said that that game was responsible for the AFL-NFL merger.


NOT true.


The AFL and NFL had agreed to merge just before the 1966-7 season, but the merger couldn't actually take place for four years because both leagues had separate television contracts that had to be honored. Somebody (Hunt? Rozelle?) came up with the idea of an AFL-NFL championship game in the meantime. If the NFL had won blowouts in all four of those Super Bowls, there would still have been a new NFL the next year, but it probably wouldn't have a "Super Bowl" but an NFL championship. I also wonder if some AFL franchises might have been dropped. As it happened, ALL the AFL teams made it into the new league, and the NFL worked to continue the Super Bowl which has since not only dominated American sports, but has become a monster. But that would be the proper subject for another video.
